      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational effort — you should be able to speak in full sentences throughout. This is aerobic base work, not a fitness test. Stay in the 5:04–5:34/km range and let your body dictate where in that band you land today.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of brisk walking and dynamic leg swings before you begin running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of easy walking and light calf and hip flexor stretching.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Tuesday easy run is the foundation of your week. At VDOT 49.7, your aerobic system is already well-developed — these runs reinforce that base without adding meaningful fatigue. Think of this as active recovery from any residual tiredness from the previous week. Keep the effort genuinely easy; the physiological adaptation here happens at low intensity, not moderate.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy at 5:04–5:34/km. Use this time to settle your breathing and loosen up. No rushing — a proper warmup makes the threshold work more effective and safer.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you could speak a few words but not hold a conversation. This is your lactate threshold: the pace at which your body is just managing lactate production. Stay controlled and even-paced.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes easy jogging between cruise intervals. This is active recovery — keep moving, let your breathing settle, but don't stop.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). Second cruise interval. If the first felt controlled, match that effort here. If it felt hard, it's okay to be 2–3 seconds per km slower — effort matters more than exact pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes easy jogging recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). Final cruise interval — shorter to allow quality to be maintained. Finish strong but controlled.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy cooldown at 5:04–5:34/km. Gradually bring your heart rate down. This is when your body begins the adaptation process — don't skip it.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog at conversational pace before any threshold work. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at threshold pace in the final minute of warmup to prime your neuromuscular system.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by 5–10 minutes of static stretching focusing on quads, hamstrings, and calves.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals at threshold pace are one of the highest-value sessions for marathon preparation. At 4:12/km, you're working right at the edge of your lactate threshold — the pace at which your body can just clear lactate as fast as it produces it. Raising this threshold directly translates to a faster sustainable marathon pace. The 3-minute recovery jogs between intervals allow partial recovery while keeping the metabolic stress high. Total threshold volume today is 8 km, which is appropriate for your current fitness and training load.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals — 1km Repeats\",\"target_distance_km\":14,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":234,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy warmup at 5:04–5:34/km. Include 4 x 20-second accelerations in the final 5 minutes, building to near-interval pace, to prime your legs for the hard work ahead.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":234,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"6 x 1 km at interval pace (3:54/km) with 400m jog recovery between each. This pace targets your VO2max — your aerobic ceiling. Each rep should feel hard but controlled: you should be able to finish each one without slowing significantly. If you're fading badly on rep 4 or 5, it's okay to add 5 seconds per km — the goal is quality, not heroics. Recovery jogs should be slow (5:30–6:00/km) — resist the urge to rush them.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval at very easy effort (around 6:00/km). This is not wasted time — it's what allows you to run the next rep at quality pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy cooldown. Bring your heart rate down gradually. Notice how your legs feel — this is useful data for your next interval session.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog with 4 x 20-second accelerations building to interval pace in the final 5 minutes. This primes your cardiovascular system and neuromuscular pathways for high-intensity work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by thorough stretching and ideally 5–10 minutes of walking. Consider foam rolling your quads and IT bands if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the engine-building sessions of your marathon plan. Running at 3:54/km stresses your aerobic system at its upper limit, which over weeks raises your VO2max ceiling and improves your running economy. For a 3:15 marathon goal (4:37/km race pace), a strong VO2max gives you a much larger aerobic buffer — meaning marathon pace will feel more sustainable. Saturday placement gives you a full day of rest before Sunday's long run, which is intentional.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":140,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km at the very easy end of your easy range (5:34/km). Your body needs time to warm up on long runs — starting conservatively protects you from early fatigue that compounds over 26 km.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":100,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"20 km at easy aerobic pace (5:04–5:34/km). This is the bulk of your long run. Stay genuinely easy — if you're running with someone, you should be able to hold a full conversation. The aerobic adaptations (mitochondrial density, fat oxidation, capillary development) happen at this intensity. Don't be tempted to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4 km at marathon pace (4:28/km). This is the key teaching moment of the long run — running marathon pace on tired legs. This is exactly what race day will feel like. Focus on form: tall posture, relaxed shoulders, quick cadence. If this feels very hard today, that's useful information — it means your easy pace earlier was too fast, or you need more recovery. Adjust next week accordingly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":6,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 5 minutes at very easy effort, transitioning to a walk. Don't stop abruptly after the marathon pace finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of walking and dynamic stretching (leg swings, hip circles, ankle rotations). The first 2 km of running should be at the very easy end of your pace range — treat them as a moving warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5–10 minutes after finishing. Prioritize nutrition within 30–45 minutes (carbohydrate and protein). Light stretching of major muscle groups. Consider an ice bath or cold shower if legs feel heavy.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This long run builds on your recent 26 km effort from March 20th. The structure — 22 km easy followed by 4 km at marathon pace — is a classic marathon-specific stimulus. Running marathon pace at the end of a long run teaches your body to recruit fast-twitch fibers when glycogen is depleted, which is precisely the challenge of the final 10 km of a marathon. Your current long run fitness is strong; this week we're maintaining volume while adding a small quality component at the end. Total weekly volume this week is approximately 63 km, a modest step up from your recent 62 km week — well within the 10% progression guideline.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
